Function to calculate pairwise locatyion distance based on relative frequency of morphs

dist_morph_freq<-function(data,localities,morphs,method="euclidean"){
#make sure the data is a data frame
data<-as.data.frame(data)
# localities unique values
localities<-unique(localities)
#create empty template
rownames(data)<-localities
comparisons<-expand.grid(localities,localities)
#generate empty matrix
result_guide <- matrix(NA, nrow = length(unique(comparisons$Var1)), ncol = length(unique(comparisons$Var1)))
rownames(result_guide) <- colnames(result_guide) <- unique(comparisons$Var1)
#
comparisons$value<-NA
for(cmp in 1:nrow(comparisons)){
#locations to compare
locA<-as.vector(comparisons[cmp,"Var1"])
locB<-as.vector(comparisons[cmp,"Var2"])
#If it is the same locality move to the next
if(locA==locB){
    comparisons[cmp,"value"]<-0
    result_guide[locA,locB]<-0
    next
}
#counter
value<-0
count_morphs<-1
while(count_morphs<length(morphs)){
locA_total<-sum(data[locA,morphs])
locB_total<-sum(data[locB,morphs])
#difference in freq
tmp_diff<-(data[locA,morphs[count_morphs]]/locA_total)-(data[locB,morphs[count_morphs]]/locB_total)
#apply the formula
tmp_val<-tmp_diff^2
#add the value
value<-sum(value,tmp_val)
#move to the next morph
count_morphs<-count_morphs+1
}
#When finished add the final value to the dataframe and matrix
comparisons[cmp,"value"]<-sqrt(value)
result_guide[locA,locB]<-sqrt(value)
result_guide[locB,locA]<-sqrt(value)
}
result_list<-list(result_guide,comparisons)
names(result_list)<-c("square_matrix","pair_comp")
return(result_list)
}

Association between colour frequency and not correlated climatic variables

Lets explore the regressions with the two datasets used, AWAP and Chelsa, making pairwise comparisons and all the morphs. We will use not correlated variables based on the results obtained on the file dates_activity_climaticdata.md

Chelsa Multiple Regression on distance Matrices

The independent variables are:

-Precipitation -Minimum temperature

Model with all morphs

result_dist_freq<-dist_morph_freq(data=sites_freq,localities=sites_freq$locality,morphs=c("females_orange","females_black","females_white"))
set.seed(65456)
multiple_reg_model<-ecodist::MRM(as.dist(scale(result_dist_freq$square_matrix))~as.dist(scale(dis_geo))+as.dist(scale(dist(sites_freq$chelsa_pr)))+as.dist(scale(dist(sites_freq$chelsa_tasmin))),method = "linear",nperm = 100000,mrank = FALSE)

Linear models morph relative frequency vs climatic variables

Considering that the frequency is a bounded variable, lets use a logit transformation

logit<-function(var){res<-(var+0.01)/(1-(var+0.01))
  return(log(res))
}

Chelsa Linear models significant variables

Calculate frequencies relative frequencies

relative_freq<-data.frame(females_white=numeric(),females_orange=numeric(),females_black=numeric())
morphs<-c("females_white","females_orange","females_black")
for(i in 1:nrow(sites_freq)){
total<-sum(sites_freq[i,morphs])
freq<-as.numeric(sites_freq[i,morphs]/total)
relative_freq[i,]<-freq
}

add a column with the precipitation and minimum temperature

relative_freq[relative_freq==0]<-NA
relative_freq$precipitation<-sites_freq$chelsa_pr
relative_freq$tasmin<-sites_freq$chelsa_tasmin

b_col<-"black"

  geom_smooth(aes(precipitation,logit(females_white)),method='lm', formula= y~x,col=w_col)+

  geom_smooth(aes(precipitation,logit(females_white)),method='lm', formula= y~x,col=w_col)+
  geom_point(aes(precipitation, logit(females_orange)),col=o_col,size=4) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(precipitation,logit(females_orange)),method='lm', formula= y~x,col=o_col)+
  geom_point(aes(precipitation, logit(females_black)),col=b_col,size=4,alpha=0.7) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(precipitation,logit(females_black)),method='lm', formula= y~x,col=b_col)+

map of Australia

library("rworldmap")
library(sf)
map_world <- getMap(resolution = "high")
aus_map<-st_as_sf(map_world[which(map_world$ISO3=="AUS"),])
aus_map<-aus_map[1]

load chelsa variables

chelsa_variables <- stack(list.files(path = "chelsea", pattern = ".tif", full.names = TRUE))

# Extract variable names from file names
names_variables <- list.files(path = "chelsea", pattern = ".tif$", full.names = TRUE) %>% 
                    str_match(pattern = "\\w+.tif$") %>% 
                    gsub(pattern = ".tif", replacement = "") %>% 
                    as.vector()

# Assign descriptive names to the raster layers
names(chelsa_variables) <- paste0("chelsa_", names_variables)

For better visualization lets divide the map of Australia in two western and easter

Western Australia frequency colours

Cut the precipitation layer around the sites

#paleta <- colorRampPalette(c("#B47067", "#EDEDEB"))
paleta <- colorRampPalette(c("#F4E8C5", "#F1D98F","#F6EC3C","#CDDC43","#A5CE39","#7DC243","#4EB29E","#467FC1","#3952A4","#6F4A96"))
wa<-sites_freq %>% filter(state=="WA") %>% data.frame()
extent_sub <-extent(min(wa[,"X"])-1, max(wa[,"X"]+1), min(wa[,"Y"])-0.25, max(wa[,"Y"])+0.25)
#select the raster
pos_var<-which(grepl(pattern="pr",x=names(chelsa_variables))==TRUE)
int_var <- terra::mask(chelsa_variables[[pos_var]], aus_map)
int_var <- crop(int_var, extent_sub)

Plot the map

library(plotrix)
library(RColorBrewer)

plot(int_var, xlim=extent_sub[c(1,2)], ylim=extent_sub[c(3,4)], col = paleta(8), axes=T, xlab="Longitude", ylab="Latitude")

#Add the shape file
plot(aus_map[1], xlim=extent_sub[c(1,2)], ylim=extent_sub[c(3,4)],col=NA,add=T) 

#Now the points
points(wa[,"X"], wa[,"Y"], pch=19, col="black", cex=2)

colours=alpha(c("gray","black","#e65d2f"),1)
for(i in 1:nrow(wa)){
total_ind=sum(wa[i,grep(pattern="females",x=names(wa))])
freq<-as.numeric(wa[i,grep(pattern="females",x=names(wa))]/total_ind)
floating.pie(xpos=wa[i,"X"],ypos=wa[i,"Y"],x=freq,radius=0.2,col=colours)
 }
